{
  "text": "We have proved in the previous section that evaluating the Proof. Let G be a loopless graph with n vertices and let G be the graph obtained from G by attaching one loop at every vertex. It is well-known that in this situation T (G ; x, y) = y n T (G; x, y). By Theorem 2.2, we have T (B(G); a, 0) = aT (G ; a + 1, 1), and by the previous remark this is exactly aT (G; a + 1, 1) , since we are evaluating at y = 1. It follows from the results in [CITATION_1] that computing T (G; a + 1, 1) is hard if a = 0, hence the same is true for T (B(G); a, 0) .",
